fastest way to accomplish this is by reviewing other proposed changes
yourself: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The container and host should both be using UTC by default, not sure why setting everything to local time is needed?

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
> 
> The container and host should both be using UTC by default, not sure why setting everything to local time is needed?

I believe that more places will change the time zone according to their geographic location. 
For example, in China, 
we generally use CST. I believe that other regions have similar problems, which will cause inconsistencies in the container with the host time, and some problems will occur.Especially the time of the log is wrong, which is not conducive to viewing。

 We can change the host directly, but the container is not easy to modify the time zone directly, but if we set it to be the same as the host, the user can customize the time zone at will, whether it is the default utc or other time zones are consistent. I feel it is necessary

> Is this commit compatible with victoria version of masakari where notification payload will be validated[1] and 'host_status' taken out of payload will be invoked？
> 
> [1] https://opendev.org/openstack/masakari/src/branch/stable/victoria/masakari/api/openstack/ha/notifications.py#L72
> [2] https://opendev.org/openstack/masakari/src/branch/stable/victoria/masakari/engine/manager.py#L175
zhaoleilc:
yes. 
No problem with payload validated, and in fact, payload validated is a meaningless function[3]. The really limit is the payload in the schema. It can't nest object in the payload nest[4].
So an example of the payload for host failure in this commit as following:
{
    'event':'STOPPED',
    'host': 'compute01',
    'management-interface': 'down',
    'tenant-interface': 'down',
    'storage-interface': 'down',
}
I think we could to make notification payload more flexible and support object nested:
{
    'event':'STOPPED',
    'host': 'compute01',
    'host_status':{
        'management-interface': 'down',
        'tenant-interface': 'down',
        'storage-interface': 'down'
    }
}
Or just to transform the object to str:
{
    'event':'STOPPED',
    'host': 'compute01',
    'host_status':"{'management-interface': 'down', 'tenant-interface': 'down','storage-interface': 'down'}"
}

The first one, we maybe need to make dashboard more open and flexible for notification payload. I prefer the second one. What is your opinion?

[3]https://opendev.org/openstack/masakari/src/branch/stable/victoria/masakari/api/openstack/ha/notifications.py#L52
[4]https://opendev.org/openstack/masakari/src/branch/stable/victoria/masakari/api/validation/parameter_types.py#L166

[3] actually validates against https://opendev.org/openstack/masakari/src/commit/9a11cd3d6342d576b9221a1e4f49abdf05ae77a8/masakari/api/openstack/ha/schemas/payload.py
So it's more relevant. This monitor should be able to work with current code we have in Masakari core (api, engine) as there is no other code to be used available at the moment. From the spec I understand that monitor will simplify the information from all Consul clusters to send notification to Masakari in the common format.

Patch Set 9:

Is it better to replace "$(CONSUL_MANAGEMENT_ADDR)" to a list? Each
item in the list can stand for a server agent's bind_addr and http port.
Since there are three server agents running in the controller nodes for one 
network domain, we just need to set corresponding addresses and ports 
of the three server agents in the list. What's your opinion?

Patch Set 9:

> Patch Set 9:
> 
> Is it better to replace "$(CONSUL_MANAGEMENT_ADDR)" to a list? Each
> item in the list can stand for a server agent's bind_addr and http port.
> Since there are three server agents running in the controller nodes for one 
> network domain, we just need to set corresponding addresses and ports 
> of the three server agents in the list. What's your opinion?

I think for our purposes one is enough. I would more focus on the fact that we are now inflexible in that there are exactly 3 clusters to monitor; some may want 2, some may want 4 and some may be happy with 1 so we need to make it more flexible (as spec suggested).

> I think for our purposes one is enough. I would more focus on the fact that we are now inflexible in that there are exactly 3 clusters to monitor; some may want 2, some may want 4 and some may be happy with 1 so we need to make it more flexible (as spec suggested).

$(CONSUL_MANAGEMENT_ADDR) is one addr for local consul agent in management datacenter, and it is made up of the local agent's bind_addr and http port, such as '192.168.101.1:8500'.

The HA strategy is more flexible. User can define the HA strategy according to the physical environment. for example, if there is just 1 cluster to monitor management network connectivity. He just need to configrate $(CONSUL_MANAGEMENT_ADDR) in consul section of the hostmontior' config-file, change the HA strategy in 'etc/masakarimonitors/matrix.yaml' as following. Then it works as same as the existing hostmonitor by pacemaker. 
"""
---
sequence: ['manage']
matrix:
    - health: ['up']
      action: []
    - health: ['down']
      action: ['recovery']
"""
